<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-253-737  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 253 737.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Jan 1989 v62 n1 p79(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lackluster market has bright spots. (US test equipment marketforecasts)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronics magazine predicts the test and measurement equipmentmarket in the US will experience only nine percent growth fortotal sales of $6.6 billion in 1989, with a few technologies suchas application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) verificationsystems expected to swell.andP;  Growth for the automatic test systemsmarket will drop to 10.5 percent for $2.5 billion sales, while themarket for general test equipment should continue an eight percentgrowth reaching $4.1 billion.andP;  ASIC verification systems areexpected to grow by 50 percent for $75 million due to thepopularity of semicustom silicon in the industry and thecontinuing development of ASIC tools.andP;  Testing equipment vendorsin the US should do better than the figures indicate because ofstrong offshore sales in Europe and the Far East.andP;  Other specificforecasts and factors involved are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Test EquipmentMarket AnalysisForecastingGrowthSalesComputer Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Sales of IC testers 1987-1989. (graph)Sales of microprocessor systems 1987-1989. (graph)Sales of ASIC verification systems 1987-1989. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>